column2: The epiblast is well-established to emerge from the ICM. See PMID 24968703
column3: The hypoblast is well-established to emerge from the ICM. See PMID 24968703
column5: The parietal endoderm is well-established to arise from the hypoblast. See PMID 24968703
column6: The visceral endoderm is well-established to arise from the hypoblast. See PMID 24968703
column10: The embryonic visceral endoderm (EmVE) is well-established to arise from the visceral endoderm. See PMID 24968703
column11: The extraembryonic visceral endoderm (ExVE) is well-established to arise from the visceral endoderm. See PMID 24968703
column19: The primitive streak is well-established to arise from the epiblast. See PMID 24968703
column27: The nascent mesoderm is well-established to arise from the epiblast. See PMID 22170865
column31: Self, with an additional edge back to epiblast (weight 0.24) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
column34: Hematoendothelial progenitors are well-established to arise from nascent mesoderm. See PMID 28859300
column35: The cell state that we annotate as mixed mesoderm, as per original study (PMID 30787436) appears to arise from nascent mesoderm.
column37: The anterior primitive streak is well-established to arise from the primitive streak. See PMID 10611967
column38: Primordial germ cells (PGCs) are well-established to arise at the posterior primitive streak. See PMID 23125014.
column39: Self, with an additional edge back to epiblast (weight 0.24) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
column41: The definitive endoderm is well-established to arise from the anterior primitive streak. See PMID 10611967
column42: The notochord is well-established to arise from the anterior primitive streak. See PMC4844759
column47: The cell state that we annotate as blood progenitors, as per original study (PMID 30787436) appears to arise from hematoendothelial progenitors.
column49: Self, with an additional edge back to nascent mesoderm (weight 0.23) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
column50: Somatic mesoderm (tentative label; these cells called mesenchyme by PMID 30787436) appears to arise from mixed mesoderm.
column51: Self, with an additional edge back to nascent mesoderm (weight 0.23) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
column57: Self, with an additional edge back to anterior primitive streak (weight 0.29) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
column58: Self, with an additional edge back to hematoendothelial progenitors (weight 0.28) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
column59: Self, with an additional edge back to anterior primitive streak (weight 0.29) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
column60: Gut is well-established to arise from definitive endoderm. See PMID 10611967
column63: Rostral neuroectoderm has edges surpassing threshold back to epiblast (0.56) and primitive streak (0.43). See PMID 29109536
column66: Self, with an additional edge back to hematoendothelial progenitors (weight 0.28) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
column68: Extraembryonic mesoderm appears to emerge from mixed mesoderm. Note that although this cell state is related to allantois at next timepoint, in general, distinction from other mesodermal cell populations is challenging. See PMID 22855605.
column69: Self, but with higher scoring edge back to nascent mesoderm (weight 0.58) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
column70: Self, with an additional edge back to mixed mesoderm (weight 0.29) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
column71: Splanchnic mesoderm has edges surpassing threshold back to both nascent (0.72) and mixed (0.28) mesoderm. See PMID <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16304598/", target="_blank">16304598</a
column72: Self, but with higher scoring edge back to nascent mesoderm (weight 0.58) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
column74: Paraxial mesoderm A arises from the nascent mesoderm. Distinguished from other paraxial mesoderm cell states based on markers Tbx1, Pax3, and potentially corresponds to anterior paraxial mesoderm. See PMID 23081715, PMID 20692252
column75: Paraxial mesoderm B arises from the nascent mesoderm. Distinguished from other paraxial mesoderm cell states based on markers Tbx6, Dll1, and potentially corresponds to posterior paraxial mesoderm. See PMID 15986483, PMID 20692252
column76: Splanchnic mesoderm has edges surpassing threshold back to both nascent (0.72) and mixed (0.28) mesoderm. See PMID <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16304598/", target="_blank">16304598</a
column80: Caudal lateral epiblast appears to arise from primitive streak, marked by Nkx1-2 aka Sax1. See https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/045872v1
column81: Caudal neuroectoderm appears to emerge from primitive streak. See PMID 11748135.
column83: Rostral neuroectoderm has edges surpassing threshold back to epiblast (0.56) and primitive streak (0.43). See PMID 29109536
column84: Surface ectoderm appears to emerge from primitive streak and adjacent ectoderm. May reflect remaining cells of epiblast, as neuroectoderm, caudal lateral epiblast also have edges back to primitive streak and adjacent ectoderm, while epiblast associated with rostral neuroectoderm. See PMC4691128.
column85: Self, with an additional edge back to mixed mesoderm (weight 0.29) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
column87: Primitive erythroid cells are well-established to emerge from blood progenitors. See PMC3904103
column89: Paraxial mesoderm C emerges with edges back to both nascent mesoderm (0.61) and caudal lateral epiblast (0.35). See https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/045872v1
column90: Self, but with higher scoring edge back to rostral neuroectoderm (weight 0.55) that presumably reflects incomplete separation.
column92: Self, but with higher scoring edge back to gut (weight 0.62) that presumably reflects an ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation. Minor contribution (0.15) from embryonic visceral endoderm is established example of convergence.
column93: Self, with an additional edge back to definitive endoderm (weight 0.28) that could be explained by incomplete separation. See PMC4844759 and PMID 16752393
column95: Self, with an additional edge back to epiblast (weight 0.21) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
column97: The allantois is well-established to arise from the Extraembryonic mesoderm. See PMID 22855605
column100: Self, but with higher scoring edge back to gut (weight 0.62) that presumably reflects an ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation. Minor contribution (0.15) from embryonic visceral endoderm is established example of convergence.
column101: Endothelium is well-established to arise from haematoendothelial progenitors. See PMC5852632
